## Context Bag

### TRANSLATION PROBLEM — "EARTHQUAKE" IS TOO NARROW

The English word "earthquake" forces a seismological reading that neither the Greek nor the Hebrew supports. The actual words are far broader:

**G4578 (seismos)** — Strong's own definition: "a commotion, i.e. (of the air) a gale, (of the ground) an earthquake." The KJV translates this SAME WORD as **"tempest"** in Mat 8:24 (storm on the sea — no ground shaking at all). Seismos = violent commotion/upheaval of ANY kind. The KJV translators narrowed it to "earthquake" in Mat 24:7 but were forced to use "tempest" in Mat 8:24 because a sea-storm obviously isn't a ground-quake. The word doesn't change — the translators' assumption does.

**G4579 (seio)** — root verb. Strong's: "to rock (vibrate, properly, sideways or to and fro), i.e. (generally) to agitate **in any direction**; figuratively, **to throw into a tremor of fear or concern**." KJV renderings prove the breadth:
- Mat 21:10 — "all the city was **moved**" (seio) — people agitated at Jesus's entry. Not the ground — the social order.
- Mat 27:51 — earth "did **quake**" — ground shaking at crucifixion.
- Mat 28:4 — guards "did **shake**" (seio) — people trembling with fear. Same verb.
- Heb 12:26 — "I shake not the earth only, but also **heaven**" — cosmic/systemic shaking.
- Rev 6:13 — fig tree "**shaken** by a mighty wind" — a tree, not the ground.

One verb. Five applications: ground, city population, people's bodies, heaven, a tree. "Earthquake" captures exactly one.

**H7493 (ra'ash)** — Hebrew root. Strong's: "to undulate (as the earth, **the sky**, etc.; also **a field of grain**), particularly through **fear**; specifically, **to spring** (as a locust)." Applied to:
- Heavens shaking (Hag 2:6, Joel 2:10, Joel 3:16)
- All nations shaking (Hag 2:7, Eze 31:16)
- Kingdoms shaking (Isa 14:16 — "the man that did shake kingdoms")
- Walls shaking from armies (Eze 26:10)
- Islands shaking at a city's fall (Eze 26:15)
- A horse leaping/springing (Job 39:20 — "make him afraid as a grasshopper")
- Grain waving on mountaintops (Ps 72:16 — "fruit thereof shall shake like Lebanon")

**H7494 (ra'ash)** — noun. "vibration, bounding, uproar, **commotion, confused noise**, earthquake, fierceness, quaking, **rattling, rushing**, shaking." Nine KJV renderings. "Earthquake" is one of nine.

### WHAT JESUS ACTUALLY SAID IN MAT 24:7

"seismoi kata topous" — violent commotions/upheavals across various places. This includes literal ground-quakes but is NOT limited to them. The word covers: storms, social upheaval, systemic shaking, violent disturbance of any established order. Hag 2:6-7 (which Heb 12:26 quotes directly) is the defining OT use: God shakes heavens + earth + sea + dry land + **all nations**. The shaking is total — geological, political, social, cosmic. Jesus's audience, hearing seismos through the Haggai lens, would understand: God is shaking everything that CAN be shaken so that what cannot be shaken remains (Heb 12:27).

The sword-to-earthquake substitution (Jesus replacing Jeremiah's standard sword+famine+pestilence triad with earthquake+famine+pestilence) is even more significant under this broader meaning. He's not swapping one disaster for another — He's upgrading from "direct violence" (sword) to "systemic destabilization of established order" (seismos). In the "beginning of birth pains" panel, the shaking is structural, not yet personal. Personal violence (sword) enters at v9 and escalates through vv21-22.

